	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Then what do the "TV games" use?</div>
<br />
<br />They usually use either microcontrollers or programmable logic to render video. Some use actual ASICs of old consoles/computers (C64 DTV, Genesis TV games).
<br />
<br />Actually, I did some searching, and it turns out that there is an actual <a href="http://www.nuvoton-usa.com/hq/enu/ProductAndSales/ProductLines/ConsumerElectronicsIC/AdvancedToy/Game/" class="postlink">old-school-console-esque chip for sale</a> (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/65C816" class="postlink">it's even based off of the 16-bit version of the 6502!</a>) However, it's nearly impossible to order, unless you're buying tens of thousands, which is a shame considering how awesome it is. What's weird is that it was originally produced by Winbond, but I can't find it on their site.

		

